00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:50.590
to have my very first
book published.

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:52.590 position:56%
So Good Night, Monkey Boy was a book

00:15:52.590 --> 00:15:56.300
that I only had started
writing a couple weeks,

00:15:56.300 --> 00:15:57.880
really, before that meeting.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:00.560
But because I kept
coming up with new ideas.

00:16:00.560 --> 00:16:03.100
I kept challenging
myself creatively.

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:05.030
I kept sending my work out.

00:16:05.030 --> 00:16:08.420
That is how my first
book was published.

00:16:08.420 --> 00:16:10.960
So I kept writing picture books.

00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:14.000
And the books that my
publisher liked, they published.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:15.300
Like Baghead.

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:16.600
And Punk Farm.

00:16:16.600 --> 00:16:17.900
And My Buddy, Slug.

00:16:17.900 --> 00:16:19.200
And Ollie, the Purple Elephant.

00:16:19.200 --> 00:16:21.840
I have a collection
of picture books.

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:24.470
And I also have a graphic
novel series

00:16:24.470 --> 00:16:27.300 position:56%
about a lunch lady who fights crime.

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:29.890
So the very first book
was called Lunch Lady

00:16:29.890 --> 00:16:33.920
and the Cyborg Substitute, and it
was followed up by nine other books

00:16:33.920 --> 00:16:37.220
for a total of 10 books
in the series.

00:16:37.220 --> 00:16:40.960
The most recent book is Lunch
Lady and the Schoolwide Scuffle.

00:16:40.960 --> 00:16:42.260
And I'm going to tell you now.

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:43.770
I'm going to shift gears.

00:16:43.770 --> 00:16:47.180 position:56%
And now that I've told you about how
I got published, I'm going to talk

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:49.920
to you about how I got
the idea for the series.

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:53.740
And what I did with those ideas
to turn them from just a few notes

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:56.620
in my sketchbook to
be a book series.

00:16:56.620 --> 00:17:00.760
What happened was way back, when
my very first book was published.

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:03.800
I went back to my old elementary
school, Gates Lane School

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:07.950 position:56%
in Worcester, Massachusetts, to talk
to the students there about writing

00:17:07.950 --> 00:17:11.950
and illustrating and having
that first book published.

00:17:11.950 --> 00:17:14.430
And they set me up
in the cafetorium.

00:17:14.430 --> 00:17:16.600
You know what a cafetorium
is [inaudible]?

00:17:16.600 --> 00:17:18.610
Yeah. Half cafeteria,
half auditorium,

00:17:18.610 --> 00:17:21.340
depending on what's going
on at school that day.

00:17:21.340 --> 00:17:23.420
And I had a slide projector.

00:17:23.420 --> 00:17:25.380
You can ask your teachers --

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:27.690
maybe The Library of Congress has
one [inaudible] slide projector

00:17:27.690 --> 00:17:30.990
looks like, so you could see what
this was like back in the day.

00:17:30.990 --> 00:17:33.880
Way before iPads and
digital projection.

00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:36.630
And so I had a slide projector, and
I'm setting up my slide projector.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:42.050
And I looked across the
cafetorium, and there she was.

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:44.520
My old lunch lady.

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:48.040
She was busy working and getting
lunches ready for school that day.

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:49.720
So I had to stop what I was doing.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:51.020
I went over to say hello.

00:17:51.020 --> 00:17:52.840
And I said hi Jeannie, how are you?

00:17:52.840 --> 00:17:55.830
You know, she looked at me, and
I could tell she recognized me.

00:17:55.830 --> 00:17:57.130
The gears were turning.

00:17:57.130 --> 00:17:58.430
She was trying to place me.

00:17:58.430 --> 00:18:00.750
And she looked at me, and
she said Stephen Krosoczka?

00:18:00.750 --> 00:18:04.780
And I was amazed that she
knew I was a Krosoczka.

00:18:04.780 --> 00:18:07.880
But Stephen is my uncle, who's 20
years older than I am [laughter].

00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:12.120
And she had been his lunch
lady when he was a kid.

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:15.240
So she started telling me about
her grandkids, and it blew my mind.

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:16.940
I thought grandkids?

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:18.240
Wait a minute.

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:19.540
You mean you leave the school
and have a life [laughter]?

00:18:19.540 --> 00:18:22.160
I thought you lived in the kitchen.

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:26.710
I had never thought about my lunch
lady's life outside of school.

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:31.390
And this chance encounter
inspired my imagination.

00:18:31.390 --> 00:18:34.050
And I opened up my sketchbook
when I got home that day,

00:18:34.050 --> 00:18:36.380
and I started drawing
this lunch lady character.

00:18:36.380 --> 00:18:40.420
And I wrote a picture
book, not a graphic novel.

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:41.720
A picture book.

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:43.900
Remember my first picture
book had just been published.

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:46.960
I had just finished the art for
Baghead, which was my second book.

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:48.260
Which was a picture book.

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:52.560
So I thought lunch lady was meant
to be a picture book as well.

00:18:52.560 --> 00:18:55.960
And it was a story about kids
who sat at their lunch table

00:18:55.960 --> 00:18:59.350
and debated what they thought
their lunch lady did after school.

00:18:59.350 --> 00:19:01.410
And whatever their
flights of fantasy were,

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:03.200
you would see that in the art.

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:05.770
So if one kid said our lunch
lady's an opera singer.

00:19:05.770 --> 00:19:08.780
And you would turn the page, and
you would see that in the art.

00:19:08.780 --> 00:19:12.640
One of the students thought well,
maybe our lunch lady is a spy.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:13.940
And she knows karate.

00:19:13.940 --> 00:19:15.870
And she keeps the school safe.

00:19:15.870 --> 00:19:20.960
And that quickly became the
more interesting story to tell.

00:19:20.960 --> 00:19:27.330
The story of a lunch lady who is
actually secretly a super hero.

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:30.970
And she's like a spy
in the cafeteria.

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:32.800
But now that story
would no longer fit

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:34.360
into the format of a picture book.

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:38.110
A picture book is only
32 pages long.

00:19:38.110 --> 00:19:40.770
And now that I'm dealing with a
story of heroes versus villains

00:19:40.770 --> 00:19:44.420
and mysteries that would need to
be solved, I'd need a longer book.

00:19:44.420 --> 00:19:46.130
And I wasn't sure what
kind of book it would be.

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:47.430
And that didn't matter.

00:19:47.430 --> 00:19:48.750
What mattered was the story.

00:19:48.750 --> 00:19:50.460
What mattered was the character,

00:19:50.460 --> 00:19:52.680
and the characters that
would surround her.

00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:55.310
So in my sketchbook, over
the next several years,

00:19:55.310 --> 00:19:56.730
I just kept drawing this character.

00:19:56.730 --> 00:19:59.410
At one point I thought it was
supposed to be a chapter book.

00:19:59.410 --> 00:20:00.710
That didn't

00:20:00.710 --> 00:20:03.980
seem like the right fit either,
but I kept drawing the character,

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:06.010
thinking about how
she'd get around town.

00:20:06.010 --> 00:20:07.310
How she'd go undercover.

00:20:07.310 --> 00:20:10.300
I started thinking about who
the other characters were.

00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:13.980
So she has an assistant named
Betty, who helps her fight crime.

00:20:13.980 --> 00:20:15.980
She has these three meddling kids

00:20:15.980 --> 00:20:18.100
that you know they
help her fight crime,

00:20:18.100 --> 00:20:19.490
even though she doesn't
want them around.

00:20:19.490 --> 00:20:21.660
She thinks they're
going to blow her cover.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:23.760
But there's Hector,
Terrence and Dee.

00:20:23.760 --> 00:20:25.060
And they're the breakfast bunch,

00:20:25.060 --> 00:20:27.300
and they become involved
in the mysteries.

00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:31.220
And she uses items from the
cafeteria [laughter] disguised

00:20:31.220 --> 00:20:33.000
as spy gadgets.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.480
So she has a spork phone.

00:20:35.480 --> 00:20:36.780
She has a spatu-copter.

00:20:36.780 --> 00:20:39.150
She has fish stick nun chucks.

00:20:39.150 --> 00:20:41.560
Because see, if you saw your
lunch lady walking down the hall

00:20:41.560 --> 00:20:43.620
with nun chucks, you
would tell your friend,

00:20:43.620 --> 00:20:45.120
and that friend would
tell another friend.

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:46.720
Those two friends -- and
then before you knew it,

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:51.110
the whole school would know that
your lunch lady is a crime fighter.

00:20:51.110 --> 00:20:54.350
So she has to have her spy
gadgets disguised as things

00:20:54.350 --> 00:20:55.650
that you would see
a lunch lady with.

00:20:55.650 --> 00:20:56.950
Like fish sticks.

00:20:56.950 --> 00:20:58.390
She has a milk camera
to spy on the classroom.

00:20:58.390 --> 00:21:01.060
She has rubber glove suction
cups to climb the walls

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:02.360
with her yellow rubber gloves.

00:21:02.360 --> 00:21:04.200
She has a lunch tray laptop.

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:07.850
Now it was around this time
that I was invited to be a part

00:21:07.850 --> 00:21:11.760
of this book called Guys Write
for Guys Reading [phonetic].

00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:13.160
Which is edited by John Cheska.

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:15.940
And he asked his author friends

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:20.480
to make a little contribution
to this anthology.

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:23.800
Everyone would write a couple
of pages' worth of stuff.

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:25.830
And he wanted us to
connect ourselves

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:28.310
with our younger selves
to our current selves.

00:21:28.310 --> 00:21:31.970
So I thought as an artist, I
would revisit some old artwork.

00:21:31.970 --> 00:21:34.400
Now I'm very lucky that every year
my grandfather would give me a

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:35.700
storage bin.

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:37.300
He'd say save what you want.

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:38.860
And then we're going to
throw the rest of it --

00:21:38.860 --> 00:21:40.690
clean your room and
throw things away.

00:21:40.690 --> 00:21:44.100
So I was going through these bins,
and I found comics that I made

00:21:44.100 --> 00:21:46.310
as an elementary school student.

00:21:46.310 --> 00:21:49.570
I found comics that I made
as a middle school student.

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:51.260
And as a high school student.

00:21:51.260 --> 00:21:53.950
I found comics that I
made as a college student.

00:21:53.950 --> 00:21:56.410
But once my first picture
book was published,

00:21:56.410 --> 00:21:59.470
I'd kind of stopped making comics.

00:21:59.470 --> 00:22:02.800
So I found this comic that
I made in the fifth grade

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:05.060
about a character named
Lightning Man.

00:22:05.060 --> 00:22:07.750
And I realized I didn't
finish his story.

00:22:07.750 --> 00:22:11.060
So for Guys Write for Guys
Read, I continued his story.

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:15.560 position:56%
I completed his story and not only
was I redrawing a character I hadn't

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:20.870 position:56%
drawn in so many years, I remembered
what I loved about making comics.

00:22:20.870 --> 00:22:22.500
And what you can do
with the storytelling.

00:22:22.500 --> 00:22:23.800
And the action.

00:22:23.800 --> 00:22:25.100
And the pacing.

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:26.400
And the humor.

00:22:26.400 --> 00:22:27.700
With that visual storytelling
format.

00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:30.390 position:56%
And I said well, this is perfect
for the story that I've been working

00:22:30.390 --> 00:22:33.740
on for the past four and a
half years at that point.

00:22:33.740 --> 00:22:35.560
Four and a half years of sketching.

00:22:35.560 --> 00:22:37.110
A story about a crime
fighting lunch lady.

00:22:37.110 --> 00:22:39.480
I sent these pages
off to my publisher.

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:41.000
They loved the idea.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:42.730
They wanted to publish the book.

00:22:42.730 --> 00:22:45.620 position:56%
But they weren't sure how to because
they hadn't published graphic

00:22:45.620 --> 00:22:46.920
novels then.

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:48.790
They didn't have any
graphic novels on their list

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:50.090
that they were publishing.

00:22:50.090 --> 00:22:52.350
So they thought well, could we
print these books in full color?

00:22:52.350 --> 00:22:55.600
And they realized they really
couldn't because it cost a lot

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:56.900
to print a book in full color.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:23:01.770 position:56%
And they didn't want to put a book
out to stores and libraries for $15.

00:23:01.770 --> 00:23:04.170
So we thought what if these books
were printed in just black ink?

00:23:04.170 --> 00:23:07.040
And they'd be printed in you
know just black and white.

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:09.670
And so the production
costs would be low,

00:23:09.670 --> 00:23:11.070
so the retail cost would be low.

00:23:11.070 --> 00:23:16.240
But the fear was there's no color
to really draw the reader in.

00:23:16.240 --> 00:23:20.120
So ultimately, we decided to
print the book in just two inks.

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:22.050
Black ink and we would
choose a second color

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:24.590
that would become the
signature color for the series.

00:23:24.590 --> 00:23:27.070
And we chose yellow
because that is the color

00:23:27.070 --> 00:23:30.420
of the iconic dishwashing
rubber glove [laughter].

00:23:30.420 --> 00:23:32.950
So now these books are going
to happen, I need to know how

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:35.660
to draw these characters, and
every time I draw the character,

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:38.570
it needs to look like
the same person.

00:23:38.570 --> 00:23:41.970
So I draw the character over and
over and over and over again.

00:23:41.970 --> 00:23:44.410
And I train myself
so every time I draw

00:23:44.410 --> 00:23:47.730
that character it looks
like the same person.

00:23:47.730 --> 00:23:49.980
Then I set out to write the story.

00:23:49.980 --> 00:23:53.020
Now I've done about five years
of brainstorming at this point.

00:23:53.020 --> 00:23:56.100
And I like to spend more
time you know brainstorming.

00:23:56.100 --> 00:23:57.400
Sketching out the characters.

00:23:57.400 --> 00:23:58.930 position:56%
Getting to know their personalities.

00:23:58.930 --> 00:24:01.810
Before I start worrying
too much about the plot.

00:24:01.810 --> 00:24:03.940
But when I start, I'm
ready for the plot.

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:06.580
I used this device
called a story mountain.

00:24:06.580 --> 00:24:09.810
And it helps me -- as a visual
thinker and a visual learner,

00:24:09.810 --> 00:24:12.780
I like to see the whole
story mapped out.

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:14.850
And I think about the beginning.

00:24:14.850 --> 00:24:16.150
The rising action.

00:24:16.150 --> 00:24:17.450
And the climax.

00:24:17.450 --> 00:24:18.750
And the falling action.

00:24:18.750 --> 00:24:20.050
And the resolution of the story.

00:24:20.050 --> 00:24:23.420
And it's important for me to point
out to you that when I start off

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:26.680
with this blank story
mountain, I don't start here.

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:30.910
I don't have to answer the question
of what happens in the beginning.

00:24:30.910 --> 00:24:34.170
Because maybe the first idea
is the climax of the story.

00:24:34.170 --> 00:24:37.100
So I could jot that down first.

00:24:37.100 --> 00:24:39.300
And I just keep coming up
with ideas and brainstorming

00:24:39.300 --> 00:24:43.540
because I don't need to dream
up the story in the same order

00:24:43.540 --> 00:24:46.050
that my reader will
eventually read it.

00:24:46.050 --> 00:24:50.160
I dream up the story, and
I rearrange those elements

00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:53.280
of the story how I see fit
to be revealed to the reader.

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:55.600
And I make page after
page of notes to myself

00:24:55.600 --> 00:24:58.210
on what I want to happen
in the story.

00:24:58.210 --> 00:25:00.030
And I lay out the book.

00:25:00.030 --> 00:25:03.880
So a 96-page graphic novel,
I make 96 little rectangles,

00:25:03.880 --> 00:25:07.730
and I try to figure out what
event will happen on which page.

00:25:07.730 --> 00:25:10.610
And you can see I'm
moving things around.

00:25:10.610 --> 00:25:13.760
And I'm taking arrows and saying
no, this event should happen here.

00:25:13.760 --> 00:25:16.420
This event should happen
earlier or later.

00:25:16.420 --> 00:25:18.410
And every page starts
off looking like this.

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:23.630
This is a small thumbnail sketch
where I'm trying to figure

00:25:23.630 --> 00:25:26.410
out where the panels are
going to go because I need

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:28.480
to recreate the reading experience.

00:25:28.480 --> 00:25:32.840
Like when you open up a book that
has text only, your eye goes where?

00:25:32.840 --> 00:25:34.410
Your eye goes to the
top left of the page.

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:38.240
Right? And your eyes scan from left
to right, and then when you get

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:40.430
to the end of the sentence,
your eye goes back down

00:25:40.430 --> 00:25:41.790
and you scan from left to right.

00:25:41.790 --> 00:25:47.930 position:56%
So I have to, as the designer of the
graphic novel, design these panels

00:25:47.930 --> 00:25:50.660
to visually recreate
that experience.

00:25:50.660 --> 00:25:53.940
So people just naturally know
where to send their eyes.

00:25:53.940 --> 00:25:56.690 position:56%
And then when it comes to designing
the information within those panels,

00:25:56.690 --> 00:25:59.250
I have to do the same thing.

00:25:59.250 --> 00:26:02.120
So that people read
it from left to right.

00:26:02.120 --> 00:26:06.170
So I make 96 pages'
worth of sketches.

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:08.740
I'll also write out a script.

00:26:08.740 --> 00:26:11.420
A script is just what the
characters are saying,

00:26:11.420 --> 00:26:12.720
descriptions of the actions.

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:14.020
My editor will read this.

00:26:14.020 --> 00:26:15.570
She'll read the script.

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:17.320
She'll look at the sketches.

00:26:17.320 --> 00:26:18.620
She'll think about it.

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:21.200
And she'll write me
an editorial letter,

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:22.520
stating this is what's
working [inaudible]

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:25.890
but this part here,
maybe not so much.

00:26:25.890 --> 00:26:28.880
So she's pushing me to
write a better book.

00:26:28.880 --> 00:26:32.240
So I listen to her advice,
and I revise the story.

00:26:32.240 --> 00:26:34.680
And I'll write a second draft.

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:36.260
And I'll make some changes.

00:26:36.260 --> 00:26:38.140
And she'll read that second draft.

00:26:38.140 --> 00:26:41.970
And then maybe the third
draft, maybe a fourth, fifth.

00:26:41.970 --> 00:26:43.660
Sometimes up to eight drafts.

00:26:43.660 --> 00:26:47.010 position:56%
But when the story's in great shape,
I can start working on the artwork.

00:26:47.010 --> 00:26:48.430
And to create the artwork
for the books,

00:26:48.430 --> 00:26:51.670
I start by just penciling
out the characters.

00:26:51.670 --> 00:26:55.190
And I use a special pencil
called non-photo blue.

00:26:55.190 --> 00:27:00.120 position:56%
It's the special shade of blue that
won't get recognized by the scanner.

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:04.690
Because what I do is I take out ink
and I dip my brush into the ink.

00:27:04.690 --> 00:27:07.210
And I ink in the final line work.

00:27:07.210 --> 00:27:10.460
And I scan that artwork
into black and white,

00:27:10.460 --> 00:27:13.380
and the computer will only
see the black line work.

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:16.010
The computer won't see all
of those sketchy lines.

00:27:16.010 --> 00:27:17.810
Which is why you don't see
them in the finished books,

00:27:17.810 --> 00:27:20.710
but they're underneath
there in the finished art.

00:27:20.710 --> 00:27:24.910
So I always start off by drawing
the major shapes of the character.

00:27:24.910 --> 00:27:28.030
Every character is made
up of a series of shapes.

00:27:28.030 --> 00:27:29.450
And I'm creating the gesture.

00:27:29.450 --> 00:27:32.480
The gesture means what
is the character's pose?

00:27:32.480 --> 00:27:36.510
And I'll add details on top of that
gesture, and I can make changes.

00:27:36.510 --> 00:27:39.520
So maybe her arm should go
in a different direction.

00:27:39.520 --> 00:27:43.090
I'll then take out my ink, and
I'll dip my brush into the ink

00:27:43.090 --> 00:27:45.870
and draw the finished line work.

00:27:45.870 --> 00:27:49.530
And I draw with a brush because
you get a very dynamic line

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:51.000
when you draw with a brush.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:53.260
If you apply a lot of
pressure to that brush,

00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:55.130 position:56%
that line is going to be very thick.

00:27:55.130 --> 00:28:00.920
As you lift the pressure away, that
line will go from thick to thin.

00:28:00.920 --> 00:28:03.090
So as I finish each
piece of artwork,

00:28:03.090 --> 00:28:06.710
I collect on a bulletin board in
front of my desk so I can see all

00:28:06.710 --> 00:28:09.750 position:56%
of the artwork and make sure all of
the characters are looking the same.

00:28:09.750 --> 00:28:13.690
Make sure the environment that
they're in looks the same.

00:28:13.690 --> 00:28:17.670
And I take the artwork,
bring it over to my scanner,

00:28:17.670 --> 00:28:18.970
and scan it into my computer.

00:28:18.970 --> 00:28:21.290
So now this artwork
that I created by hand,

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:23.670
I can see on my computer screen.

00:28:23.670 --> 00:28:25.380
And you'll see that all of
the word balloons are empty.

00:28:25.380 --> 00:28:27.000
