00:47:25.170 --> 00:47:27.550
And I'm drawing the gesture.

00:47:27.550 --> 00:47:29.730
The gesture is like
where the limbs are.

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:31.510
Like how the character is posed.

00:47:31.510 --> 00:47:33.500
And I'm going to have her
jumping through the air.

00:47:33.500 --> 00:47:36.960
So I think about where her legs go.

00:47:36.960 --> 00:47:41.430
Not a lot of detail yet, is there?

00:47:41.430 --> 00:47:46.200
Because it's a lot easier
to make changes now.

00:47:46.200 --> 00:47:49.330
So if I were to start by drawing
the details of the character's eyes

00:47:49.330 --> 00:47:51.340 position:56%
and face and I would get to the end.

00:47:51.340 --> 00:47:52.640
And I said I want to make a change.

00:47:52.640 --> 00:47:55.090
But I spent all that time and
all that work on the detail.

00:47:55.090 --> 00:47:57.710
Because now I can look at
that and say, you know what?

00:47:57.710 --> 00:48:01.990
I'm going to make her head a
little bit smaller, like so.

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:05.980
So now on top of that gesture
sketch, I'll layer the details.

00:48:05.980 --> 00:48:08.280
So I have the character's hair.

00:48:14.450 --> 00:48:16.560
And eyes and face.

00:48:16.560 --> 00:48:19.970
And I'm pretty loose with my marks.

00:48:22.630 --> 00:48:25.000
Close her gloves.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:27.300
Her sleeves.

00:48:30.830 --> 00:48:35.180
So once I have a good foundation
down, then I would take out my ink.

00:48:35.180 --> 00:48:39.100
And again, when I'm at home, I take
a brush, and I dip it into ink.

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:41.070
That would be logistically
difficult.

00:48:41.070 --> 00:48:42.590
And I flew here by
airplane this morning.

00:48:42.590 --> 00:48:44.850
I would need something
smaller than 4 ounces.

00:48:44.850 --> 00:48:46.780
I have a big old ink jar there.

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:50.510
So, I going to use a Sharpie
marker as a stand-in for that.

00:48:50.510 --> 00:48:58.600
[ Drawing ]

00:48:58.600 --> 00:49:03.820
And again, when this artwork
-- when it gets scanned in,

00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:08.490
and I set that scanner
to black and white,

00:49:08.490 --> 00:49:14.870
the computer doesn't register
the blue pencil marks.

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:19.510
It only registers -- it can only
see that crisp black line work.

00:49:19.510 --> 00:49:22.350
[ Drawing ]

00:49:22.350 --> 00:49:25.790 position:56%
So, if you were ever able to get a
look at some of the original artwork

00:49:25.790 --> 00:49:28.270
up close, you would see all

00:49:28.270 --> 00:49:31.530
of the underworking
underneath all of the art.

00:49:31.530 --> 00:49:33.210 position:56%
But you don't see that in the books.

00:49:33.210 --> 00:49:34.510
You just see the finished lines.

00:49:34.510 --> 00:49:38.730
So you may have been under the
assumption that I start off

00:49:38.730 --> 00:49:44.640
by drawing the lines that
intricate and that's spot-on.

00:49:44.640 --> 00:49:48.250
But you see, I allowed
myself to make some mistakes

00:49:48.250 --> 00:49:50.510
with the pencil before
I went to the final art.

00:49:50.510 --> 00:49:54.610
[ Drawing ]

00:49:54.610 --> 00:49:56.480
My signature and the year.

00:49:56.480 --> 00:49:58.730
So there's lunch lady, but she --

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:01.500
there's another character that's
very important to the story.

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:06.950
And where lunch lady is made
up of a series of teardrops,

00:50:06.950 --> 00:50:10.150
there's someone else who's
made up of a series of circles.

00:50:10.150 --> 00:50:12.480
And every character
is made up of shapes.

00:50:12.480 --> 00:50:16.310
And when you boil it down
to just the main shapes,

00:50:16.310 --> 00:50:18.880
your audience could
probably tell who that is.

00:50:18.880 --> 00:50:20.560
Does anybody know who this is?

00:50:20.560 --> 00:50:22.420
That's amazing.

00:50:22.420 --> 00:50:24.110
Thank you for knowing that.

00:50:24.110 --> 00:50:25.680
That's her sidekick Betty.

00:50:25.680 --> 00:50:30.510
All I drew was a circle and a
bell, and you knew who it was.

00:50:30.510 --> 00:50:51.500
[ Background Conversations ]

00:50:51.500 --> 00:50:53.300
Thank you.

00:50:53.300 --> 00:51:00.040
[ Applause ]

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:01.580
Now that you've applauded,
I hope I don't mess

00:51:01.580 --> 00:51:03.190
up the rest of this [laughter].

00:51:03.190 --> 00:51:05.460
You can't take back that
applause, no matter what I do.

00:51:05.460 --> 00:51:07.260
It's mine now.

00:51:07.260 --> 00:51:34.760
[ Drawing ]

00:51:34.760 --> 00:51:36.560
Okay. So, well thank you.

00:51:36.560 --> 00:51:41.420
[ Applause ]

00:51:41.420 --> 00:51:45.220
I'm going to leave you with
one final lesson before we go.

00:51:45.220 --> 00:51:46.770
And this lesson that I'm
going to give you, too,

00:51:46.770 --> 00:51:51.810
you can apply to your
characters that you're inventing.

00:51:51.810 --> 00:51:54.250
And we're going to
talk about emotions.

00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:58.900
Because illustration is all about
visually communicating the story.

00:51:58.900 --> 00:52:01.740
So how a character
feels is communicated

00:52:01.740 --> 00:52:04.240
by their facial expression.

00:52:04.240 --> 00:52:07.850
So could you show me with
your faces, just your faces,

00:52:07.850 --> 00:52:10.530
what does it look like
when you're really happy?

00:52:10.530 --> 00:52:12.640
When you're really
happy, you smile real big.

00:52:12.640 --> 00:52:13.940
You can see your teeth.

00:52:13.940 --> 00:52:19.260
And when you smile, your lips
push up and your cheeks push up,

00:52:19.260 --> 00:52:22.510
and it creates a little
line underneath the eyes.

00:52:22.510 --> 00:52:25.730
[ Drawing ]

00:52:25.730 --> 00:52:27.200
Like so.

00:52:27.200 --> 00:52:29.360
[ Drawing ]

00:52:29.360 --> 00:52:31.970
And there, with the
character looks happy.

00:52:34.150 --> 00:52:35.450
Could you please show me --

00:52:35.450 --> 00:52:38.190
show me what it looks like
when you're really angry.

00:52:38.190 --> 00:52:40.050
You're angry.

00:52:40.050 --> 00:52:42.060
Your eyebrows cross.

00:52:42.060 --> 00:52:46.190
And what happens is your eyebrows
are pushing together towards the

00:52:46.190 --> 00:52:51.330
center of your face, and it's
wrinkling up your forehead a bit

00:52:51.330 --> 00:52:54.770 position:56%
And you also -- you were so angry --

00:52:54.770 --> 00:52:58.400
you were so angry that you
tilted your heads down.

00:52:58.400 --> 00:53:00.670
And you were looking up.

00:53:00.670 --> 00:53:05.350
So you can have those angry
eyebrows with that little line,

00:53:05.350 --> 00:53:08.520
but see how there's space
between the eyes and the eyebrows?

00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:11.360
It's not going to be the case here.

00:53:11.360 --> 00:53:14.840
Those eyebrows are going to be
covering the very top of the eyes

00:53:14.840 --> 00:53:16.640
because your head is tilted down.

00:53:16.640 --> 00:53:22.540
[ Drawing ]

00:53:22.540 --> 00:53:24.360
Show me what it looks like
when you're really sad.

00:53:24.360 --> 00:53:25.660
Like it was just an awful day.

00:53:25.660 --> 00:53:27.240
You're really sad.

00:53:27.240 --> 00:53:28.540
Your eyebrows.

00:53:28.540 --> 00:53:30.340
Okay, your eyebrows all came up.

00:53:30.340 --> 00:53:35.040
[ Background Conversations ]

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:37.510
And you all pouted a little
bit with your lips right there.

00:53:37.510 --> 00:53:41.810
[ Background Conversations ]

00:53:41.810 --> 00:53:44.710
Now show me what it looks like --

00:53:44.710 --> 00:53:49.920
show me what it looks like
when you're scared [yelling].

00:53:49.920 --> 00:53:52.780
Your eyes all got really big.

00:53:52.780 --> 00:53:55.360
Your eyes got really big.

00:53:55.360 --> 00:54:02.550
And the trick to showing
that a character is scared is

00:54:02.550 --> 00:54:06.510
that not only are the eyes bigger
but the pupils are smaller.

00:54:06.510 --> 00:54:12.510
[ Drawing ]

00:54:12.510 --> 00:54:16.700
[ Laughter ]

00:54:16.700 --> 00:54:19.650
Now there are so many other
emotions that we could cover.

00:54:19.650 --> 00:54:23.750 position:56%
And I encourage you to explore those
on your own by just sitting in front

00:54:23.750 --> 00:54:25.370
of a mirror and making faces.

00:54:25.370 --> 00:54:28.700 position:56%
Actually when I'm at home, my family
catches me doing this all the time.

00:54:28.700 --> 00:54:30.000
I'll be drawing.

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:33.410
And I'm making the face of the
character that I'm drawing.

00:54:33.410 --> 00:54:34.750
I'm becoming that character.

00:54:34.750 --> 00:54:39.940
But now this applies if
your character is human,

00:54:39.940 --> 00:54:43.510
or if your character
is maybe a lion.

00:54:43.510 --> 00:54:49.180
[ Laughter ]

00:54:49.180 --> 00:54:50.980
Maybe a pig.

00:54:50.980 --> 00:54:57.180
[ Laughter ]

00:54:57.180 --> 00:54:58.980
Maybe a space alien.

00:54:58.980 --> 00:55:02.100
[ Laughter ]

00:55:02.100 --> 00:55:03.400
Maybe an elephant.

00:55:03.400 --> 00:55:09.870
And with an elephant, I can use
that trunk to show the emotion.

00:55:09.870 --> 00:55:14.250
Or if I were drawing a rabbit,
I could use those ears to show

00:55:14.250 --> 00:55:18.110
that the character was
sad or surprised or happy.

00:55:18.110 --> 00:55:20.680
So out of everything that I
talked about this morning,

00:55:20.680 --> 00:55:27.630
what I hope that you remember the
most is that my career, my journey,

00:55:27.630 --> 00:55:32.010
as an author and as an artist,
began when I was your age.

00:55:32.010 --> 00:55:34.960
And I want you to make sure that
you consider yourselves authors

00:55:34.960 --> 00:55:36.260
and illustrators.

00:55:36.260 --> 00:55:40.730
And that please don't wait for
this to be a school assignment.

00:55:40.730 --> 00:55:44.580
Because it does not need
to be a required thing

00:55:44.580 --> 00:55:46.580
because it's so much fun.

00:55:46.580 --> 00:55:49.790
It's so much fun to
use your imagination.

00:55:49.790 --> 00:55:53.250
Escape from your real
life for a little bit.

00:55:53.250 --> 00:55:55.430
And take a blank piece of paper

00:55:55.430 --> 00:55:59.560
and pour your imagination
out onto that paper.

00:55:59.560 --> 00:56:03.450
So after school, on your own,
without any grownup asking you to,

00:56:03.450 --> 00:56:07.330
get a hold of some paper
and make awesome things.

00:56:07.330 --> 00:56:08.660
Okay? Thank you guys so much,

00:56:08.660 --> 00:56:10.620
and thank you the Young Reader
Center for having me today.

00:56:10.620 --> 00:56:12.420
Thank you.

00:56:12.420 --> 00:56:17.310
[ Applause ]

00:56:17.310 --> 00:56:18.610
Thank you.

